{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Project-supplied review criteria + project-invariant compliance (unified cross-gate registry)\n\n## Context\n\nrebar's review gates ship a fixed, built-in set of criteria. Client projects have their own\nstandards and invariants — naming, layering, banned APIs, architectural rules — the built-in\nset can't express. This epic lets a **project supply its own review criteria** and declare\n**architectural invariants** the gates check, **beyond** the built-in set.\n\n**Cross-cutting:** it must serve **plan-review, code-review (`b744`), and any future\ncriteria-based gate** through **one shared registry**. (Spun out of `5fd2` as follow-on F8;\nconfig-UX sibling `55de`/F5.)\n\n**Posture (from `5fd2`, binding):** coach-not-block, advisory-by-default, **fail-open\n(ironclad)**, polyglot / broad client base, convergent-by-construction, **reuse existing\nmachinery — no plugin system, no new DSL**.\n\n## Design decisions (settled in brainstorm; see rationale comment)\n\n1. **Unified criterion data model + shared registration/discovery/schema/eval plumbing;\n   per-gate application** (gate-scoped routing inside the shared record; postures do NOT\n   converge).\n2. **Two authoring forms, no project code in the gate:** DET \"invariants\" = declarative\n   pattern rules via the existing grounding scan facade; LLM criteria = prompt files.\n3. **Any criterion (DET or LLM) may block** — `--force`-escapable, folds into the signed\n   (kind-keyed) attestation coverage, can never rebind a built-in.\n4. **Blocking is project-owned policy.** rebar surfaces the same eval/calibration instruments\n   it uses on its built-ins; the maintainer decides blocking + threshold. Trust is theirs.\n5. **Reuse existing formats** (prompt front-matter, the `criteria_routing.json` schema,\n   Inspect-AI fixtures, the scan facade). No new formats.\n6. **Explicit activation; presence != active.** Routing/threshold in a `.rebar/` overlay\n   (§ Overlay schema); namespaced + additive; the overlay may re-tune or **disable** a\n   built-in (recorded in coverage).\n7. **Eval tooling in scope** = fixture/discrimination harness + calibration/agreement view.\n   **Out** = REVIEW_RESULT FP-replay (F1; gate-agnostic, inherited later).\n8. **An \"invariant\" is just a blocking criterion** (usually DET). One mechanism.\n9. **Visual editor extended** to author project criteria (reuses `/library/create`).\n\n## Overlay schema, activation & caching (clears E2/G6/T8)\n\n- **File:** `.rebar/criteria_routing.json`, reusing each gate's packaged `criteria_routing.json`\n  schema, keyed by gate:\n  `{\"plan_review\": {\"<id>\": {…routing…}}, \"code_review\": {\"<id>\": {…}}, \"activate\": [\"project.<name>\", …]}`.\n- **Per-criterion routing** reuses existing keys: plan-review `{exec, applies_at, block_threshold,\n  default_posture, facet, checklist}`; code-review `{exec, applies_to (globs), block_threshold,\n  blocking_enabled}`. (Note the deliberate posture divergence — plan-review derives blocking\n  from `default_posture`; code-review uses an explicit `blocking_enabled`; the shared\n  `threshold_for` must honor BOTH — do not \"fix\" the divergence.) **DET criteria also carry\n  `fail_mode: open|closed`** (default `open` for project invariants; `closed` for the built-in\n  security class) — see § DET-invariant scan scoping.\n- **`exec` vocabulary:** `1-TURN` / `2-STEP` / `AGENT` (LLM tiers) or **`DET`** (pattern-rule\n  invariant; code-review already uses `DET` inline). A **DET criterion has no prompt** — descriptor\n  assembly must treat prompt resolution as OPTIONAL for `exec: DET` (today `_descriptor_from_prompt`\n  unconditionally calls `get_prompt(...)` and raises if absent). A DET criterion's \"rubric\" is its\n  detector rule id (`.rebar/detectors/`), not a `.md`; only its routing entry is required.\n  **DET fallback descriptor shape** (a `_descriptor_from_prompt` DET branch that skips\n  `get_prompt`): `name` = routing `name` or id; `scenario` = the detector rule's `message`/\n  description from its `.rebar/detectors/<id>` envelope; `facet` = routing `facet` (default = id);\n  `checklist` = empty. This is an expand-contract change (add the DET branch; existing prompt-backed\n  callers unaffected).\n- **Namespace / collision (load-time, located error):** a net-new project criterion id MUST be\n  `project.<name>`-prefixed. An overlay entry keyed by an **un-prefixed built-in id** is a\n  **re-tune/disable** of that built-in (allowed, §Design 6). A `project.`-prefixed id equal to a\n  built-in id, or a duplicate project id, is **rejected at load** (a project id can never rebind\n  a built-in).\n- **Activation:** a criterion runs only if listed in `activate` (presence in the file ≠ active).\n- **Discovery — `effective_criteria(repo_root)`** = `CANONICAL_LLM`/`OVERLAY_IDS` ∪ activated\n  project ids (each resolved via `get_prompt(id, repo_root)` for its rubric + the overlay routing\n  entry). Route it through **every** vocabulary site: plan-review `load_criteria`,\n  `check_registry_coverage`, and the **workflow Pass-1 batch vocabulary** (`workflow_ops` builds\n  the `include_<ID>` fan-out from the canonical set at workflow-definition time — project ids must\n  enter it too, else an activated criterion never fans out; the `include_<id>` output key must\n  sanitize the `project.<name>` id, e.g. `.`→`_`, to a valid workflow output key); code-review\n  `OVERLAY_IDS`,\n  `routing_index`, `threshold_for`.\n- **Caching (clears G6 cache bug):** keep `_routing_index()` `@lru_cache`d for the **packaged**\n  index (immutable per binary); add `effective_routing(repo_root)` (uncached, or keyed by\n  `(repo_root, overlay mtime)`) that merges the overlay; extend `prompt_library._invalidate_caches()`\n  (already clears `load_criteria`/`_routing_index`). A RED test must prove no cross-repo routing\n  leakage in the long-lived MCP server.\n\n## Attestation & invalidation (clears G6/COH/E1; reuses kind-keyed attest infra)\n\n- **`registry_version(repo_root=None)`** additionally hashes the `.rebar/` overlay when\n  `repo_root` is given; thread `repo_root` through **every** caller — `claim_gate_check →\n  compute_validity`, and also `drift_refresh_candidate` and `remediation_mode_candidate` (which\n  call `registry_version()` today without it) — so activating/editing/disabling a criterion\n  **invalidates a prior attestation at claim time** (today it hashes packaged routing only — the\n  change does not invalidate).\n- **Disable recorded in coverage:** a disabled built-in is listed in a `disabled_builtins: [ids]`\n  field in the verdict `coverage` dict (and folded into the signed manifest) so the cert reflects\n  reduced coverage rather than silent omission; the field is additive/expand-contract (absent on\n  old certs).\n- **Cross-gate:** applies to **any gate attestation backed by the shared registry** (plan-review\n  now; code-review once it signs — see Migration; code-review signs nothing today).\n- **Expand-contract / back-compat:** the new regver basis is additive; an existing attestation\n  lacking it is treated as **stale → re-review**, never a crash. Overlay absent ⇒ regver == today\n  (no invalidation churn).\n\n## DET-invariant scan scoping & fail-open (clears COH)\n\n- A DET invariant runs as a **whole-repo content scan** via the shared `grounding.engine_b.scan`.\n  The **oracle always fails open** (engine binary absent / parse-error / timeout → `abstain`). The\n  **consumer** then applies the criterion's **`fail_mode`**: `open` (default for project invariants)\n  turns an abstain into a skip = PASS; `closed` (the built-in security class, via the existing\n  `apply_failclosed`) turns an abstain into a BLOCK. So generalizing `code_review/detectors.py` =\n  making its currently-hardcoded fail-closed behavior a per-criterion `fail_mode` that **defaults\n  open** — the two behaviors are one code path parameterized by `fail_mode`, not a contradiction.\n  Matches are **gate-scoped**: code-review filters matches to the **diff** (as\n  `code_review/detectors.py` already does); plan-review has no diff, so a DET invariant checks the\n  plan's declared intent and repo context — an invariant that inherently needs a diff is **N/A at\n  plan time (fail-open)** and belongs to code-review.\n- Because matches are gate-scoped (diff / plan), pre-existing whole-repo violations are **not**\n  surfaced as new work — this is why **no baseline/grandfathering** is needed (reconciles the\n  Out-of-scope note).\n- **LLM fail-open:** an LLM criterion configured to block whose call errors/times out **fails\n  open** (skipped, does not block) — same rule as DET.\n\n## What exists vs. what we build (grounded to file:line, 2026-06-30; incl. b744 worktree)\n\n**Already built (reuse):**\n- **Shared three-pass kernel** `review_kernel/` (verify/decide/coach) — **both** gates already\n  consume it (code-review via `code_review/workflow_ops.py`); the divergence-risky core is\n  already unified.\n- **A DET pattern-rule → finding consumer already exists:** `code_review/detectors.py` calls the\n  shared `grounding.engine_b.scan` + `load_registry` (which already unions `.rebar/detectors/`) +\n  `apply_failclosed` (consumer-side fail-CLOSED; oracle stays fail-OPEN). Generalizable — the only\n  hardcoded bits are the `rebar.builtin.security.` prefix + 2 criterion mappings.\n- **Per-criterion blocking is DONE:** `code_review/registry.threshold_for` + kernel Pass-3 +\n  detector fail-closed.\n- **Project extension points:** `.rebar/prompts/` (rubric override), `.rebar/<gate>_moves.json`\n  (additive coach moves), `.rebar/detectors/` (project pattern rules), `.rebar/evals/` (fixtures).\n- **Kind-keyed attestation infra** (`plan_review/attest.py`); Inspect-AI eval seam; discrimination\n  scorers + Cohen's κ + parity metrics.\n\n**Net-new (build):**\n- **Open the closed criterion vocabularies** (`CANONICAL_LLM`, `OVERLAY_IDS`) via\n  `effective_criteria(repo_root)` — THE precondition; a project criterion is silently skipped\n  today regardless of overlay.\n- **`.rebar/` routing overlay + activation + cache isolation** (§ Overlay schema).\n- **A shared descriptor abstraction:** code-review has only `routing_index()` (raw routing), no\n  `load_criteria`-style merged descriptor and no `facet/checklist/…`; unification introduces/\n  generalizes one and reconciles the `blocking_enabled` vs `default_posture` postures + exec-tier-\n  polymorphic (prompt-less DET vs LLM) criteria.\n- **Generalize the DET-scan consumer** beyond the security prefix (data-driven criterion↔detector\n  map) so arbitrary project invariants route; make the fail-open/closed behavior a per-criterion\n  `fail_mode` (today `apply_failclosed` is hardcoded closed; default project invariants to open);\n  expose to plan-review too.\n- **Per-criterion eval runner** — `eval_solver.run_case` is a closed 3-id dispatch (raises\n  otherwise) + a validate-only CLI; add a criterion-aware runner + a live CLI + the\n  **calibration/agreement view** (rendering is net-new; κ/parity metrics exist).\n- **Attestation port to code-review** + `registry_version(repo_root)` + disable-coverage +\n  claim-gate invalidation (§ Attestation).\n- **Editor live must-fire/must-not-fire preview** — a new **synchronous** editor endpoint\n  `POST /criterion/preview` `{criterion_id | inline(prompt+routing), fixture}` →\n  `{verdict: \"fire\"|\"no-fire\", finding?: <findings.py finding shape>, rationale: str}`, reusing\n  the per-criterion eval runner behind the `agents` extra + credentials, with a **configurable\n  timeout (default 60s)** (no prompt-execution endpoint exists today — the editor's `POST` set is\n  `/save`, `/prompt/save`, `/validate`, `/library/create`). **Spike gate:** if a single sync\n  preview does not return within the timeout on the reference model, fall back to an async\n  job+poll shape rather than blocking the editor's `ThreadingHTTPServer` handler.\n- **Routing derivation/validation pipeline** (`criteria_routing.json` is hand-maintained; no\n  generator/drift gate).\n\n## Migration & compatibility\n\n- **Callsites** to route through `effective_criteria`: plan-review `load_criteria`,\n  `check_registry_coverage`, `attest.registry_version`, `workflow_ops` vocab; code-review\n  `OVERLAY_IDS`, `routing_index`, `threshold_for`.\n- **Preserve the `review_code` / `code_review/shim.py` `review_result` return shape** — it is a\n  back-compat surface consumed by MCP `review_code`, CLI `rebar review-code`, and the Gerrit\n  `review_bot/adapter.py`.\n- **Rollback = fail-open to packaged:** overlay absent ⇒ both gates behave exactly as today. The\n  unification is expand-contract; a misbehaving unified registry falls back per-gate. The\n  `registry_version` code change is itself expand-contract (old certs → stale, never crash).\n- **Docs deliverable:** an ADR under `docs/adr/` + a `CLAUDE.md` \"project-supplied criteria\"\n  section document the unified registry contract, the overlay merge/activation semantics, and the\n  attestation-invalidation protocol, plus a how-to for authoring/activating/eval'ing/blocking on a\n  criterion (the concrete target for the docs AC).\n\n## Build order (risk-ordered MVP; clears G5 thin-slice)\n\nProve the full loop on the riskiest piece first, then fan out:\n1. **MVP slice** — fix the `_routing_index` cache isolation + `effective_criteria(repo_root)`\n   discovery → activate ONE project LLM criterion from the `.rebar/` overlay → run it in\n   plan-review Pass-1 → surface its finding → `registry_version` reflects the overlay so a change\n   invalidates the attestation. This proves author→activate→run→surface→attest end-to-end.\n2. Generalize the DET-invariant scan consumer (data-driven map).\n3. Per-criterion eval runner + calibration view.\n4. Editor live-preview + authoring extension.\n5. **Unify** plan-review + code-review registries into `rebar.llm.criteria` (after `b744` lands).\n\n## Dependency\n\n**Blocked on `b744`** (code-review; WS1–WS5 landed on `worktree-code-review-capability`, WS6 =\nGerrit voter pending). The `review_kernel` is already shared; the remaining fork is the\nregistry/descriptor + posture + vocabulary layer, unified after b744 lands (temporary\nduplication accepted).\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n- A project can add its own criteria (DET pattern-rules + LLM prompts) that run in plan-review,\n  code-review, and future gates via **one shared registry**.\n- A project can declare architectural invariants (blocking DET criteria) the gates check.\n- The project **owns blocking/threshold policy** per criterion, informed by the same\n  eval/calibration instruments rebar uses on its built-ins.\n- **No project code executes in the gate**; unsupported stacks fail open.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `effective_criteria(repo_root)` opens the closed vocabularies (`CANONICAL_LLM` +\n      `OVERLAY_IDS`) so an activated project criterion is loaded/run by the gate; routed through\n      every vocabulary callsite (see Migration).\n- [ ] `.rebar/criteria_routing.json` overlay per the § Overlay schema: gate-keyed, namespaced,\n      explicit `activate` list, load-time collision/rebind rejection (a located error).\n- [ ] Overlay merge is cache-isolated per repo (packaged index stays cached; overlay is not); a\n      RED test proves no cross-repo routing leakage.\n- [ ] The overlay may re-tune or disable a built-in; a disable is recorded in attestation coverage.\n- [ ] Project DET pattern-rule invariants run through the generalized (data-driven)\n      `engine_b.scan` consumer and surface as blocking-capable findings; fail-open on\n      engine-binary-absent / parse-error / timeout per the criterion's `fail_mode` (default `open`\n      → skip = PASS; security-class `closed` → block).\n- [ ] Project LLM prompt criteria run through the shared registry with gate-scoped routing; an\n      LLM-block criterion that errors fails open.\n- [ ] A shared `rebar.llm.criteria` layer that both plan-review and code-review consume, preserving\n      `review_code`'s `review_result` shape. **Gated on `b744`:** built against plan-review first and\n      adopted by code-review once b744 lands (this AC is the post-b744 unification child).\n- [ ] `rebar criteria eval <id>` runs a project criterion's must-fire/must-not-fire +\n      discrimination fixtures live (extending the closed solver dispatch) and prints a calibration\n      view per criterion: **recall** (= fraction of must-fire fixtures it fires on), **false-accept**\n      (= fraction of must-not-fire fixtures it wrongly fires on), **Cohen's κ** and **agreement %**\n      (criterion verdict vs the fixture's labeled expectation); FP-replay (F1) out of scope.\n- [ ] A project criterion may block (project-configured threshold/posture), `--force`-escapable;\n      verdict + coverage fold into the signed attestation. (No-rebind is enforced at load time —\n      see the overlay-schema AC.)\n- [ ] `registry_version(repo_root)` hashes the overlay; activating/editing/disabling a criterion\n      invalidates a prior attestation at claim time for **any** gate backed by the shared registry;\n      old attestations lacking the field are treated as stale (re-review), not a crash.\n- [ ] The visual editor authors a project criterion (prompt + routing form) and runs a live\n      must-fire/must-not-fire preview via a new `POST /criterion/preview`\n      (`{criterion, fixture} → {verdict, finding?, rationale}`; reuses the eval runner; bounded\n      timeout; gated on the `agents` extra). A spike first validates sync-execution feasibility.\n- [ ] A routing derivation/validation pipeline for the overlay: **load-time** validation (invalid\n      routing is a located error, not a silent skip) **plus a CI drift/parity gate** (mirroring the\n      `reviewers/index.json` regenerate+diff gate).\n- [ ] An ADR + `CLAUDE.md`/`docs/` section documents the unified registry contract, overlay merge\n      + activation semantics, and the attestation-invalidation protocol for downstream gate\n      implementors; plus a how-to for authoring/activating/eval'ing/blocking on a criterion.\n\n## Out of scope\n\n- Arbitrary project-authored code in the gate (declarative pattern-rules only).\n- Graph-level invariants (transitive layering / cycles / containment) — wrap an existing tool\n  later; not a new DSL.\n- Baseline/grandfathering — matches are gate-scoped (diff / plan), so pre-existing whole-repo\n  violations are never surfaced as new work.\n- REVIEW_RESULT FP-replay calibration (F1); the richer config-UX (`55de`/F5); the b744 Gerrit\n  voter (WS6)."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1782871195411108001,"uuid":"39e866fb-8c44-4d80-a7f0-6c46109b43b4"}